# Reframe: Parts → Burnout Recovery App
**Working title:** Recharge (or any name — this is internal reference)
**Stack:** Keep everything. Next.js + ElevenLabs + Cloudflare Workers + Durable Objects.
**Format:** Web app first. PWA install for phone. No App Store needed yet.

---

## What This Is

A daily voice coaching app for high performers running below capacity. Three short sessions per day — each one under a minute — that track your recovery across the three dimensions of burnout: energy, meaning, and capability. The app asks one sharp question per session, reflects back in one or two sentences, and builds a longitudinal picture of where you're depleted and what's shifting.

The north star metric is your **Recovery Index** — a single number that moves week over week, built from your scores across three dimensions. That's the one thing you open the app to see improving.

**Target user:** You. Tech founders, finance operators, builders running at high output who don't have time for therapy and don't need it — they need signal on where they're leaking energy and a structured way to address it daily.

---

## Scientific Framework

Based on Christina Maslach's burnout research — the most cited work in occupational psychology, published in peer-reviewed journals and freely referenceable.

**The three dimensions you track:**

| Dimension | What it measures | Voice in the app |
|---|---|---|
| Exhaustion | Where energy is going that doesn't feel sustainable | The Energy Audit |
| Cynicism | Disconnection from meaning, purpose, or people | The Meaning Finder |
| Efficacy | Sense of competence and impact in your work | The Capability Mirror |

**ACT (Acceptance and Commitment Therapy)** principles remain in the underlying prompt logic — they're already built into the repo and map cleanly to burnout recovery. Keep them as the scaffolding for how questions evolve, don't remove them.

**What you cannot use:** The Maslach Burnout Inventory (MBI) is a copyrighted psychometric test owned by Mind Garden, Inc. Do not reproduce its specific questions. Build your own measurement logic using the three dimensions above — the science is public, the instrument isn't. Attribution line to use anywhere: *"Based on published occupational research from the University of California, Berkeley."*

